description: When Princess Diana‚Äôs boy Harry fell in love with a gorgeous American starlet, people went aaahhh. Then things got even better. Ewan McGregor, Rebecca Ferguson and newcomer Kyliegh Curran star in the supernatural thriller, directed by Mike Flanagan, from his own screenplay based upon the novel by Stephen King.Still irrevocably scarred by the trauma he endured as a child at the Overlook, Dan Torrance has fought to find some semblance of peace. title: Why Planes Don't Fly Over Antarctica
tags: no-fly zones|Taj Mahal|Buckingham Palace|Kennedy Space Center|Camp David|Disney Corporation|George Washington‚Äôs House|Makkah|Himalayan Mountains|Tibet|Earth‚Äôs north pole|Earth‚Äôs south pole|Antarctic|Area 51|Pantex Nuclear Facility|Disney World|Disneyland|airplanes|planes|onboard|traveling by plane|air travel|airplane travel|aircraft|civil aviation|military aviation
description: Have you ever wondered if there are things an airplane simply can‚Äôt or won‚Äôt do? It turns out that airplanes have strict rules regarding their pathways in the sky ‚Äì for safety reasons, and for the sake of staying friendly with continental neighbors. Some of the places they‚Äôre not allowed to fly over might surprise you!For example, planes won‚Äôt fly directly over the Earth‚Äôs poles and over the Pacific Ocean. You can't see planes over Tibet and over the City of Mecca. The airspace over Walt Disney World and Disneyland is also a no-fly zone. The same applies to Area 51 but we don't know why.  Other videos you might like:A Plane Disappeared And Landed 37 Years Later https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0AoJddnJ6SA&10 Things You Didn‚Äôt Know About Flight Attendants https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V1neQzgKL38&That's Why Airplane Seats Are Almost Always Blue https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0esI1IrxCmk&TIMESTAMPS:Antarctica 0:50The Earth‚Äôs Poles 1:20the Pacific Ocean 2:43Tibet 3:19The City of Mecca 4:09When It‚Äôs Too Hot 4:35George Washington‚Äôs House 5:23Disney World and Disneyland 5:56Pantex Nuclear Facility 6:43Camp David 7:08Kennedy Space Center 7:56Area 51 8:30Buckingham Palace 9:11The Taj Mahal 9:46#Planes #aviation #brightsideSUMMARY:- Due to the windy and snowy conditions of the Antarctic mountains, this area is more prone to white-outs; the pilot wouldn‚Äôt be able to see at all! - The Earth‚Äôs north pole has super strong magnetic fields that are constantly changing ‚Äì their reach and direction can change by miles a year!- Planes won‚Äôt fly over Tibet. This is largely due to the Himalayan Mountains. First of all, if a plane has to land in an emergency situation, mountains aren‚Äôt exactly the ideal impromptu runway.- There‚Äôs a strong magnetic field in Makkah. As mentioned earlier, a magnetic field can cause navigational problems for pilots.- George Washington‚Äôs House is considered a National Historic Landmark, so to prevent further damage to the historic home, even from air vibrations in the sky, the airspace above George and Martha‚Äôs house was declared a no-fly zone. - In 2003, the Disney Corporation put ‚Äútemporary‚Äù no-fly zones over both their parks, but somehow, they just stuck.- Due to the many presidents and world-wide VIPs that visit Camp David, the airspace above the whole compound is a no-fly zone for safety reasons. - Kennedy Space Center in Florida is a no-fly zone. There‚Äôs a lot of NASA and U.S. Airforce activity that goes on here ‚Äì pretty important work. So safety for all parties is the top priority. - Buckingham Palace is meant to protect the Queen and the royal family, so of course a no-fly zone was established above it. - The Indian government place a no-fly zone above the area of the Taj Mahal in 2006 to safeguard this important historical building and the many tourists who come to witness its majesty. title: What We Know About India's Failed Lunar Landing
tags: isro|vikram|chandrayaan 2|moon|beresheet|crash|lroc
description: Chandrayaan 2 was a highly ambitious mission for ISRO, and while the orbiter is working the lander failed during the last few moments before touch down. Based on the handful of public statements, and images from mission control it looks like braking from orbital velocity worked correctly, but the transition to fine control for descent may have resulted in a tumbling spacecraft which impacted the surface at about 100m/sec. However I hope more information comes along soon.Cees Bassa's tweets with the radiotelescope trace can be found here:https://twitter.com/cgbassa/status/1170075259804012544?s=20

title: The Ending Of It: Chapter Two Explained
tags: looper|looper movies|ending|explained|ending explained|it chapter 2|it chapter two|it: chapter 2|it: chapter two|it chapter 2 ending|it chapter two ending|it: chapter 2 ending|it: chapter two ending|it chapter 2 ending explained|it chapter two ending explained|it: chapter 2 ending explained|it: chapter two ending explained|it chapter two book v movie|it chapter two book vs movie|it chapter 2 explained|it chapter two explained|it: chapter 2 explained
description: Thumbnail Image by William Gray ‚Üí https://www.instagram.com/willgray_art/ How well does the sequel to 2017's It adapt Stephen King's classic novel while tying up all the loose ends from the first installment? Let's roll up our sleeves, wade into the sewers and dig into the details of how the saga ends. This is the ending of It: Chapter Two explained.And before you open the door labeled very scary, be warned: Spoilers await you.Stephen King's novel It isn't just the story of a creepy clown terrorizing some kids and then returning to do it all over again when they're adults. There's a whole cosmology to the saga, which includes a giant, godlike turtle that coughed up the known universe when it had a tummy ache. Aside from a few subtle nods here and there, the movies mostly sidestep the ancient, interdimensional mythology of the book, but one element does show up in It: Chapter Two - the true form of It.When he goes to visit the Shokopiwah tribe and takes one of their vision-granting concoctions, Mike learns that It came to Earth in a meteor strike that left a crater in Derry, and is made up of Deadlights, mostly orange but sometimes-blue spheres of light of immense power. Though the lights can be seen in brief moments in the first film, It appears entirely as deadlights as Chapter Two reaches its climax, and even after taking on other forms, the deadlights are still visibly powering the creature, becoming increasingly weaker as the Losers literally bring It down to size.It's true form is revealed because the Losers perform the Ritual of Ch√ºd, a ceremony that differs pretty wildly in the movie from the way it works in the book. The movie's take on the ritual involves each member of the club burning a token of his or her childhood and reciting a chant to make the Deadlights turn dark, then trapping the Deadlights inside a pyramid-shaped relic Mike stole.The ritual is the key to defeating It in the book, though it takes two tries 27 years apart. But the Losers' attempt essentially fails in the movie, at least at first. That's because it's revealed Mike lied to everyone in an attempt to simply bring them all back together. The ritual wasn't successful before when the Native Americans tried to do it, and it doesn't kill It when the Losers try it this time, either. At least, not until they've gone through the wringer just a little bit more so they can truly overcome the fears that feed It.  Keep watching the video to see the ending of It: Chapter Two explained!#ItChapterTwo #EndingExplained #ItDeadlights | 0:23The Ritual of Ch√ºd | 1:27Childhood fears, adult anxieties | 2:21The hypochondriac cuts loose | 3:24Brotherly baggage | 4:17Home at last | 5:06The end of obsession | 6:09Scars of the past | 7:20

description: Hey Guys! Welcome to episode #4 of my thrift store makeover series where I take something I've found out of a thrift store (or actually, in this case i found it at a yard sale, but still) and I strip it down and give it a makeover. This always involves a lot of color, sometimes glitter, and a lot of PAINT. Hope you enjoy!This time I'm flipping a wooden carousel wall hanging that I found at a yard sale. I believe this is a vintage item, but it hasn't aged well at all. It definitely needs a makeover. I want to hang this in my art room (ART ROOM TOUR: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x6xKb3mA8DY) which happens to be full of color and cutesy stuff.
